node.text: More than 2 million women have left the workforce during this pandemic. We’ve got to get women back to work. The American Rescue Plan will do that.

node.title: VP on Women in the Workforce

node.text: On this 20th anniversary of September 11, 2001, we must challenge ourselves to look back—for the sake of our children and their children. For that same reason, we must also look forward. We must also look toward the future. Because in the end, that is what the 40 passengers and crew members of Flight 93 were fighting for: Their future, and ours.

node.text:
From Day One, President Biden and I have been committed to fighting for Historically Black Colleges and Universities. Our Administration provided billions in relief to HBCUs through the American Rescue Plan. And our Build Back Better Agenda goes even further. We plan to make college more affordable, including at HBCUs. We also plan to put billions of dollars toward HBCU research facilities and developing the next generation of leaders in STEM.

Thank you, Hampton University for welcoming me to your home by the sea today. This HBCU grad was happy to celebrate #HBCUWeek with you!

node.text:
Hampton—like HBCUs everywhere—are not just competing, they are leading on STEM education. Our Build Back Better Agenda would make an historic investment in R&D infrastructure for HBCUs. Today I met with students at Hampton to hear their vision for the future. 
 
Investments in STEM programs on campuses like @_hamptonu are critical to keeping our nation competitive in this new era. I toured Hampton’s Center for Atmospheric Sciences to see the impressive work students are doing to study our climate.

node.text:
Every year, students and alumni across America from Historically Black Colleges and Universities come together to celebrate the rich history and important contributions of these esteemed institutions.

I am a proud graduate of an HBCU. My time at @howard1867 shaped me into the person I am today. At Howard, I was on the debate team and pledged to @akaalphachapter. I also ran for my very first elected office as the freshman class representative of the Liberal Arts Student Council.

Today, the extraordinary students at our nation's HBCUs are focused and driven. They are at the forefront of scientific research, interning on Capitol Hill, starting their own businesses, and transforming our country through poetry, music, and dance. HBCU students know there are no false choices. You can do anything.

HBCU students—@POTUS and I are counting on you and investing in you. Our world faces many challenges and we need our brightest minds to take them on. The most important lesson I learned while I attended an HBCU: You do not only have the capacity to be great. You have the responsibility to live up to that potential. So speak your truth. Lead with purpose. And remember that wherever you go, you are never alone, because your HBCU family is always with you. Happy #HBCUWeek!

node.text: Mexico is one of our most important economic partners. Yesterday, I spoke at the re-launch of the U.S.-Mexico High Level Economic Dialogue about deepening the ties between our nations, so that our people enjoy greater prosperity and a greater quality of life.

Today we celebrate the American Labor Movement, how it fought for workers and transformed the way we live and work. 

Happy Labor Day everyone.

node.text: Yesterday, I spoke with three leaders in California who are doing everything they can to contain and suppress these destructive wildfires and keep communities safe. Firefighters and emergency response workers are heroes and they have our complete support.

node.text: Today I had the privilege of swearing in Ken Salazar as our new Ambassador to Mexico. He has dedicated much of his life to public service, and I am confident he will help us strengthen our partnership with one of our most important economic and security partners.

node.text:
Yesterday, the Texas legislature passed sweeping legislation with a singular aim: making it harder for Texans to vote. The new law limits the very options that allowed historic numbers of Texans, especially citizens of color, to vote safely in our last election.

Earlier this summer I met twice with those Texas lawmakers who did everything in their power to try to stop this bill from passing. They raised the alarm bells on this assault on our democracy, and I commend them for it.

Now, Congress must act to protect the voting rights of all Americans by passing the For the People Act and the John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act.

node.text: 58 years ago today, hundreds of thousands of Americans marched on Washington in the name of equality, freedom, and justice. Today, we continue to fight for the right to vote. The Senate must pass the For the People Act and the John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act.

node.text: Today, on the three-year anniversary of his passing, I paid my respects to an American hero, Senator John McCain. At this site in 1967, then-Lieutenant Commander McCain was shot down. We honor his sacrifice in Vietnam, and the sacrifice of all our men and women in uniform.
